        keyVerse: { ref: 'Romans 8:15', text: 'For you did not receive the spirit of slavery to fall back into fear, but you have received the Spirit of adoption as sons, by whom we cry, "Abba! Father!"' },
        devotional: 'ABBA is the word a child says to a father in Aramaic — closer to "Daddy" than to "Father" in formal English. Paul leaves the word untranslated on purpose. The Spirit of God prays this word THROUGH you when you cry out. Christianity is not just permission to address God — it is family-level intimacy with Him.\n\nMost Christians live as servants long after they have been adopted. They obey, but they do not relax. Try praying with "Abba" or "Daddy" at the start today. If it feels weird — that is normal. It is also probably evidence of how far away you have been living from a Father who has been waiting at the door the whole time.',
        prompt: 'Adopted. Heir. Cry "Abba." Try praying using "Daddy" today.',
